depict a small round pelt shield in action, but by the middle of the 3rd century BC it was replaced by thureos, adopted by the Achaean League and the Boeotians by 270 BC. e. Plutarch describes Achaean citizens equipped with thureos as skirmishers, as peltasts, but having spears for close combat. However, despite the presence of spears, thureophores were not reliable in hand-to-hand combat due to the fact that they were light infantry. in Greece, but also in other areas, for example, in Anatolia. Sword battles with thureos (thureomachy) have become part of many Greek sports competitions.